## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Excellent pairing (e.g., Viscaria, Timo Boll ALC). The crispness of the outer carbon helps offset the dense, slightly dead feel of the hybrid rubber on soft shots.
    - Inner Carbon: Very good for players wanting maximum dwell time and spin, though it may feel slightly sluggish from mid-distance.
    - All-Wood: Works beautifully with stiff 7-ply woods (e.g., Clipper Wood) for close-to-table attackers.
    - Mismatch Cases: Avoid soft, flexible 5-ply all-wood blades unless you are purely a close-to-table control looper; the setup will lack finishing power.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Highly recommended. It matches the longer, more powerful strokes typical of forehand mechanics.
    - Backhand: Generally not recommended for average players due to its heavy weight and requirement for high-impact force. Only suitable for advanced players with elite backhand technique.

